UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1475
1 A JOINT RESOLUTION designating the Representative Bob DeWeese Memorial
2 Highway in Jefferson County.
3 WHEREAS, Bobby "Bob" Miller DeWeese was a son of this Commonwealth,
4 having been born in the La Center community of Ballard County on November 8, 1934;
5 and
6 WHEREAS, raised by his cherished grandparents, Grace and John R. Miller, Bob
7 DeWeese was drawn to the medical profession early in life by assisting the man who
8 would later become his stepfather, Dr. William Coffee, in his veterinary practice; and
9 WHEREAS, Bob DeWeese began his higher education at the University of
10 Kentucky in 1953 and went on to graduate from the University of Louisville Medical
11 School. He practiced medicine at several hospitals in Louisville, and proudly served as
12 president of the Louisville Surgical Society and chief of staff at multiple institutions; and
13 WHEREAS, Bob DeWeese turned to politics in the 1990s, and it was in this area
14 that he made an indelible mark on the Commonwealth. He was elected to the Kentucky
15 House of Representatives in 1992, and served that body for 24 years as State
16 Representative of the 48th District, including as the Republican Caucus Chairman for 14
17 years; and
18 WHEREAS, after retiring from medicine, Bob DeWeese became a fierce advocate
19 for healthcare issues in the General Assembly while maintaining his trademark sense of
20 loyalty to his home city of Louisville. He was instrumental in the construction of the
21 Westport Road-Watterson Expressway interchange, and became renowned for his ability
22 to work with Kentucky's colleges and universities. An ardent supporter of the "Bucks for
23 Brains" program, he tried throughout his years in public service to help institutions of
24 higher learning carry out their missions and to see that the Commonwealth's learners
25 were given the opportunity to flourish, just as he had once done; and
26 WHEREAS, in 2000, Bob DeWeese was honored with the Dr. Nathan Davis Award
27 by the American Medical Association for his work as an outstanding legislator; and
Page 1 of 2
